Part 2

The Punarjeevan shelter had no gatekeeper. The rusted iron gate sat half-open, held in place by an old red brick to keep it from swinging in the constant dust kicked up by the trucks on the nearby bypass road. 

Vikram had walked four kilometers down the highway before a truck driver offered him a lift on a flatbed carrying concrete pipes. He sat on the wooden bench of the driver's cabin, the smell of grease and raw diesel filling his lungs, saying nothing until the driver let him off near the bypass milestone.

Sarita was sitting in the front courtyard under the thin shade of a drumstick tree. She had a large red plastic tub of dry chillies in her lap, sorting the split ones from the whole with practiced, rhythmic movements. 

Her saree was made of faded cotton, the color of wet river brick. She didn't look up when the gate creaked on its hinges.

"We don't have visitor hours on Friday," she said, her hands moving through the pile.

"I am not a visitor," Vikram said, carrying his leather bag.

She stopped sorting the chillies, the red dust rising in the hot air. She looked at his leather bag, then down at his dusty leather shoes.

"Rohan signed?" she asked.

"He signed."

"And you?"

"I signed first," Vikram said.

Sarita went back to the chillies, making a dry, rustling sound as she moved them. "This is not a guesthouse, Mr. Ahuja. We don't have city comforts here."

"I know."

"We don't have clean sheets. We don't have separate rooms. The men sleep in the side hall—six on the floor, and one on the wooden bench near the window."

"I can sleep on the floor," Vikram said, setting his bag down on the stone verandah.

She stood up, placing the plastic tub on the stone ledge of the well. Her hands were slightly red from the dry chilli dust.

"You are thirty-five," she said, looking him directly in the eye. "Same age as me. You have sat in a leather executive chair for ten years. You think this is a retreat. A peace-finding exercise to feel good."

"No," Vikram said.

"It isn't," she said, her voice dropping. "The municipal corporation cuts our water line twice a month because we don't pay the grease money. The local school refuses our children. And three times a year, someone dies in the back room and we have to argue with the local police to let us bury them without a post-mortem."

She wiped her hands on the edge of her saree. "I have the virus, Vikram. I have had it for six years. My husband gave it to me before he died. Most people in this house have it. You don't."

"I know," Vikram said.

"Then why are you standing at my gate with nothing but two shirts in a bag?"

"Because nobody here calls me Ahuja Sahib," Vikram said.

Sarita studied his face for a long moment. The hot wind from the bypass brought the dry smell of burnt rubber from the tyre repair shops down the road.

"Go to the well," she said finally, her voice softening. "Wash the dust off. Ramu's nephew brings the tea at five. It is cheap tea. We don't have sugar today, only jaggery."

---

The well water was cold. Vikram drew a bucket, the rough hemp rope biting against his palms. 

He washed his face, his neck, and his arms, the dust of the Nandyal roads and the study room sliding off his skin into the drain.

A girl was standing near the drumstick tree, watching him. She was thin, wearing an oversized blue frock that had a small tear near the hem, and her hair was tied in two tight plates. 

She looked fourteen, perhaps fifteen, her collarbones standing out sharp under the thin fabric.

"You are the factory man," she said, her voice direct.

"My name is Vikram," he said, wiping his face with his sleeve.

"Sarita didi said you own the big trucks."

"My brother owns them now," Vikram said.

She came closer. Her eyes were large, dark, and had the specific, unblinking curiosity of a child who had grown up around adults who had stopped hiding things from her.

"I am Ananya," she said.

"Do you go to school, Ananya?"

"The school closed for me," she said, without any sadness in her voice. "They said my blood is bad."

"Who said that?"

"The headmaster. He told Sarita didi that if I sit near the other girls, their parents will stop paying the fees. Sarita didi argued. She has a very loud voice when she's angry. But the gate remained locked."

She looked at his leather bag near the well. "What is inside?"

"Two shirts," Vikram said.

"No toys?"

"No."

He glanced at his bag near the well. Two shirts. That was all.

"I have a wooden horse," she said proudly. "Ramu's nephew made it. It has only three legs, but it stands if you lean it against the wall."

Vikram smiled. It was the first real smile since the doctor's phone call at four in the morning. "Show me," he said.

---

They sat on the low stone wall of the well. The wooden horse was small, carved from a dry branch of the drumstick tree. 

Ananya leaned it carefully against the bucket. It stood.

"See?" she said, pointing at it. "It doesn't need the fourth leg. It is just for show."

Sarita came out carrying a steel kettle and three mismatched glasses. She set them on the stone ledge. 

The tea was dark red. No milk. The jaggery had turned it the color of boiled tamarind.

"Drink," she said.

Vikram held the glass. The heat of the glass was direct, burning his fingers slightly. He took a sip. 

The jaggery was sweet, but the tea was strong and bitter at the edges. Outside, the bypass traffic went on, the trucks honking, the dust rising. 

But inside the courtyard, the red tea tasted of nothing but the well water and the shade of the drumstick tree.

"It is good," Vikram said.

Sarita sat on the well wall beside Ananya. She put her arm around the girl's shoulder, pulling her close. 

"It is cheap," Sarita said, looking at the road. "But it is ours."

Vikram drank. He looked at the three-legged horse, at Ananya's laughter as she knocked it down and set it up again, and at Sarita's quiet face. 

The fourteen hundred crore had gone to Nandyal. The office keys were left on the teak wood desk. 

But the red tea in his glass smelled better than any tea he had ever had in a boardroom.

[End of Part 2]
